The paper deals with signal detection and estimation in the presence of unknown transmission parameters, which is a common problem in information theory (cs.IT) and signal processing (cs.SP). The use of sparsity and compressed sensing is a key aspect of the proposed method, which suggests that it could also be relevant to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.MM) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), where these techniques are often used. Finally, the paper discusses the complexity and performance tradeoffs of different acquisition schemes, which could be of interest to the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI), where similar tradeoffs are often studied.
